\begin{frame}{Support and resistance}
Highs and lows are very important: they show where buying and selling pressure was sufficient to change direction
\pause
\begin{itemize}[<+-| alert@+>]
\item At the high
\begin{itemize}
\item There was more selling than buying
\item Those willing to bet that the security was over-valued had more fire-power than those willing to bet that it was undervalued
\end{itemize}
\item At the low
\begin{itemize}
\item There was more buying than selling
 Those willing to bet that the securities was undervalued had more fire-power than those willing to bet that was overvalued
\end{itemize}
\item There is a change of direction that these points
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Use of support and resistance}
As a result, support at resistance are used for 
\begin{itemize}[<+-| alert@+>]
\item Identifying when sentiment has changed
\item Setting \textbf{Take-profit}
\item \textbf{stop-loss} 
\end{itemize}
\pause
However, 
\pause
\begin{block}{}
This can mean that they are self-fulfilling: stops and take-profits are triggered at particular points
\end{block}
\end{frame}

