\begin{frame}{Moving average}
A moving average will just take the average of closing prices and smooth to remove some of the noise
\pause
\begin{block}{}
\begin{equation*}
MA3 = \frac{1}{3} \sum_{i = -3}^{i=0}(P_{t-i})
\end{equation*}
\end{block}
\pause
\begin{itemize}[<+-| alert@+>]
\item Different time periods
\item Short MA or price crossing longer MA is a signal
\item May be tailored to the market or contemporary conditions
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Exponentially-weighted moving average}
The longer the moving average the more of the past that is taken account of.  However, it may make sense to weight the recent past more highly than that which is far gone. 
\pause
\begin{block}{}
\begin{equation*}
EWA_t = \alpha P_t + (1 - \alpha) EWA_{t-1}
\end{equation*}
\end{block}
\pause
Where $\alpha$ is a smoothing factor between 0 and 1.  A higher value put more weight on the present. This must be initialised by setting $EMA_t = P_t$. 
\end{frame}

